Carrefour, LVMH, Total, Valeo, Vergnet: French Equity Preview

-- B y   H e a t h e r   S m i t h
-- 
2011-05-30T04:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-30/carrefour-lvmh-total-valeo-vergnet-french-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  France’s  CAC 40 Index (CAC)  rose 33.76 points, or 0.9 percent, to
3,950.98 in Paris. The broader SBF 120 Index advanced 0.8
percent to 2,979.43 points.  Carrefour SA (CA)  : The world’s second-largest retailer
was contacted by Cia. Brasileira de Distribuicao Grupo Pao de
Acucar Chairman Abilio Diniz in recent weeks to discuss ways to
combine Carrefour’s Brazilian stores with Pao de Acucar’s
network, the Wall Street Journal reported yesterday, citing
unidentified people familiar with the matter. The shares gained
0.3 percent to 30.34 euros.  Ipsen SA (IPN)  : Chief Financial Officer Claire Giraut,
will leave the French drugmaker as of Sept. 1, the company said
on May 27. The stock fell 0.6 percent to 28.47 euros.  LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton SA (MC)  : The world’s
biggest luxury-goods maker’s acquisition of Bulgari SpA will
allow LVMH to double its hard-luxury division turnover, Borsa &
Finanza reported May 28, citing Bulgari Chief Executive Officer
Francesco Trapani. The shares rose 1.6 percent to 118.35 euros.  Total SA (FP)  : Europe’s third-biggest oil company
acquired a 25 percent stake in a Qatari offshore hydrocarbon
exploration license, state-run Qatar Petroleum said yesterday in
a statement. Cnooc Ltd., which was awarded the license to
explore and develop the field in 2009, will retain a 75 percent
stake, Qatar Petroleum said. The stock rose 0.9 percent to 39.54
euros.  Valeo SA (FR)  : France’s second-largest car-parts maker
aims to grow via acquisitions, Boersen-Zeitung cited Chief
Financial Officer Robert Charvier as saying in an interview. The
company could finance takeovers with existing funds, the German
newspaper reported May 28. The shares climbed 2.6 percent to
42.58 euros.  Vergnet (ALVER)  SA: The maker of windmills said its
holders approved an 18 million-euro ($26 million) capital
increase. The shares declined 0.7 percent to 4.61 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Heather Smith in Paris at 
 hsmith26@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Anthony Aarons at   aaarons@Bloomberg.net . 